{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17262"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17262"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9952"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9952"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63476"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"8114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10726"},{"type":"tags","id":"10728"},{"type":"tags","id":"10730"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA genetic counsellor is reviewing a family pedigree that shows the following pattern:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDisease appears in every generation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBoth males and females are affected\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEach affected person has an affected parent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EApproximately 50% of offspring are affected\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following inheritance patterns best explains these pedigree findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitochondrial inheritance","Autosomal recessive inheritance","X-linked recessive inheritance","X-linked dominant inheritance","Autosomal dominant inheritance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pedigree demonstrates classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E. Key characteristics include vertical transmission (disease appears in every generation), affected individuals having an affected parent, and roughly 50% of offspring being affected. Males and females are equally affected because the gene is on an autosome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect patterns can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - Typically shows horizontal transmission with unaffected parents, and disease may skip generations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - While showing vertical transmission, affected fathers pass the trait to all daughters but no sons\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked recessive inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - Predominantly affects males, with rare female cases. No male-to-male transmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - Only transmitted from mother to all offspring, never from father to children\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of autosomal dominant conditions include Huntington disease, familial hypercholesterolaemia, and Marfan syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autosomal dominant inheritance shows vertical transmission with affected individuals in every generation","In autosomal dominant inheritance, affected individuals typically have an affected parent","Males and females are equally affected in autosomal dominant inheritance patterns"],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S, Cleaver R. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics and Genomics. 16th ed. Edinburgh: Elsevier; 2021. ISBN: 9780702079665.","Goldberg ML, Fischer J, Hood L, Hartwell L, Aquadro C. Genetics: From Genes to Genomes. 8th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Education; 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63476"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17262"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63476"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T11:52:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T11:52:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9952"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78054"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4945","links":{"self":"https://a